      <div rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211" type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn">
        <p><pb n="1v"/><lb n="1"/><g type="mangala"/>svasty<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> uccakalpā<sic>t</sic> mahārājaughadevas tasya puttras tat-pādānuddhyāto mahādev<unclear>yāṁ</unclear><!--
The maṅgala symbol seems quite complex. It includes a horizontal dash (bulging upwards) similar to that visible in other Uccakalpa plates, but also has a vertical component, resulting in a vague cross shape. The vertical may be a scratch rather than part of the symbol.
--><lb n="2"/>kumāradevyām utpanno mahārāja-<space type="binding-hole"/>kumāradevas tasya puttras tat-pādā<lb break="no" n="3"/>nuddhyāto mahādevyāṁ jayasvāminyā<space type="binding-hole"/>m utpanno mahārāja-jayasvāmī tasya <lb n="4"/>puttras tat-pādānuddhyāto mahādevyāṁ rāmadevyām utpanno mahārāja-vyāghra<unclear>ḥ</unclear> <lb n="5"/>tasya puttras tat-pādānuddhyāto mahādevyām ajjhitadevyām utpanno mahārāja<lb break="no" n="6"/>-jayanāthas tasya puttras tat-pādānuddhyāto mahādevyā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> muruṇḍadevyām utpa<lb break="no" n="7"/>nno mahārāja-śarvvanāthaḥ kuśalī vaiśyavāṭake brāhmaṇādīn kuṭumbi<lb break="no" n="8"/>nas sarvva-kārū<sic>n</sic>ś ca samājñāpayati</p>
        <p>vidita<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> vo stu yathaiṣa grāmo <lb n="9"/>mayācandrārkka-samakālikaḥ sodraṅgaḥ soparikaraḥ A-cāṭa-bhaṭa<lb break="no" n="10"/>-prāveśyaḥ halikā-kara-sametaḥ c<sic>au</sic>ra-daṇḍa-varjjitaḥ Uttarāpatheya-khāthānā<lb break="no" n="11"/>-puttra-viśākhadatta-śaktibhyāṁ Etat-puttra-prapauttra-tatputtrādy-anukrameṇa tāmra<!--
Halder emends to puttra-pauttra-prapauttra. I think this is unnecessary, the phrasing is identical in almost all Uccakalpa grants I've processed so far.
--><lb break="no" n="12"/>-śāsanenāgrahāratvenāti<choice>
            <sic>sya</sic>
            <corr>sr̥</corr>
          </choice>ṣṭaḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> Ābhyām api mayānumoditakaṁ yatho<lb break="no" n="13"/><unclear>pa</unclear>ri-likhitaka-krameṇaiva sva-puṇyābhivr̥ddhaye sva-pratiṣṭhāpitaka-bhagavata<!--
Halder emends bhagavata to bhagavat. To me, bhagavataḥ sounds just as plausible, and there may in fact be a visarga after ta, but this is the very edge of the plate. In either case, the first svāmi in the next line seems superfluous - unless perhaps there are two deities installed by the two brothers, a bhagavata-svāmi and a kārttikeya-svāmi?
--><lb break="no" n="14"/>-svāmi-kārttikeya-svāmi-pādānāṁ khaṇḍa-phuṭṭa-pratisa<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied>skāra-karaṇāya <lb n="15"/>vali-caru-sattra-gandha-dhūpa-dīpa-taila-pravarttanāya cātisr̥ṣṭaḥ</p>
        <p><pb n="2r"/><lb n="16"/>te yūyam eṣāṁ samucita-bhāga-bhoga-kara-hiraṇyādi-pratyāyo<unclear>pa</unclear>naya<unclear>ṁ</unclear> kari<lb break="no" n="17"/>ṣyathājñā-śravaṇa-vidheyāś ca bhaviṣyatha<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied><space type="binding-hole"/> ye cāsmad-va<sic>n</sic>śotpadyamānaka-rājāna<unclear>ḥ</unclear>
<lb n="18"/>tair iya<sic>n</sic> dattir na vilopyānumodanī<space type="binding-hole"/>yā yathā-kālañ ca pratipālanīyā<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied><lb n="19"/>samucita-rājābhāvya-kara-pratyāyāś ca na grāhyāḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied>
yaḥ <choice>
            <sic>ra</sic>
            <corr>i</corr>
          </choice>mā<sic>n</sic> datti<sic>n</sic> lopayet saḫ pa<lb break="no" n="20"/>ñcabhir mahā-pātakair upapātakaiś ca saṁyuktas syād<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> uktañ ca mahābhārate <lb n="21"/>bhagavatā veda-vyāsena vyāsena</p>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="1">
          <l n="a">sva-dattām para-dattām bā</l>
          <l n="b">yatnād rakṣa yudhiṣṭhi<lb break="no" n="22"/>ra</l>
          <l n="c">mahīm mahīmatāñ chreṣṭha</l>
          <l n="d">dānāc chreyo nupālanaṁ</l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="2">
          <l n="a">prāye<sic>n</sic>a hi narendrāṇāṁ</l>
          <l n="b">vidya<lb break="no" n="23"/>te n<choice>
              <sic>a</sic>
              <corr>ā</corr>
            </choice>śubhā gatiḥ</l>
          <l n="c">pūyante te tu satataṁ</l>
          <l n="d">prayacchanto vasundharāṁ</l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="3">
          <l n="a">bahubhi<lb break="no" n="24"/>r vasudhā bhuktā</l>
          <l n="b">rājabhiḥ sagarādibhiḥ</l>
          <l n="c">yasya yasya yadā bhūmis</l>
          <l n="d">tasya tasya <lb n="25"/>t<choice>
              <sic>ā</sic>
              <corr>a</corr>
            </choice>dā phalaṁ</l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="4">
          <l n="a">ṣaṣ<sic>ṭh</sic>iṁ varṣa-sahasrāṇi</l>
          <l n="b">svargge modati bhūmidaḥ</l>
          <l n="c">Acchettā cānu<lb break="no" n="26"/>mantā ca</l>
          <l n="d">tāny eva narake vaset<!--
Halder reads vasat, emending to vaset. I think the e mātrā is clear.
--></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="5">
          <l n="a">sarvva-sasya-samr̥ddhā<sic>n</sic> tu</l>
          <l n="b">yo hareta vasundharāṁ</l>
          <l n="c"><lb n="27"/>śva-viṣṭhāyāṁ kr̥mir bhūt<unclear>v</unclear>ā</l>
          <l n="d">pitr̥bhis saha majjate</l>
        </lg>
        <p>likhitaṁ sambatsara<lb break="no" n="28"/>-śate Eka-navaty-uttare dvir-āṣāḍha-māsa-divase daśame bhogika-phālgu<lb break="no" n="29"/>dattāmātya-naptrā bhogika-varāhadinna-puttreṇa mahā-sāndhivigrahika<lb break="no" n="30"/>-manorathena<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> <choice>
            <sic>dūtakar</sic>
            <corr>dūtako</corr>
          </choice> mahāvalādhikr̥ta-kṣattriya-śivaguptaḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied>
					<pb n="3r"/><lb n="31"/>halikā-kara-pratimocanābhilekhāyāne pi dūtakaḥ Uparika<!--
The reading does indeed seem to be °abhilekhāyāne. However, while characters are very loosely spaced in the line, the akṣaras khā-ya-ne practically flow together. Very probably an original °lekhane pi was corrected to °lekhāyāpi for some reason. Compare IN00087/31.
--><lb break="no" n="32"/>-mātr̥śivaḥ</p>
        <p>Aghāṭāḥ yatra U<space type="binding-hole"/>ttarasyāṁ diśi garttā yāvat-sanmukha<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied><!--
Halder emends to yāvat-saṁmukhaḥ, translating "trench as far as (its) mouth".
--><lb n="33"/>pūrvveṇa karddamilā nadī<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> dakṣiṇena garttā punaḥ punar āvarttakena yāvat-sanmukhaḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied><!--
Halder again emends to yāvat-saṁmukhaḥ.
--><lb n="34"/>gavāyanagarttikā-grāma-samīpe kacchako madhya<unclear cert="low">me</unclear> garttāyāḥ dakṣiṇāmukh<unclear>o</unclear><!--
Halder translates kacchaka as "a low hill", noting that it is dongar in Central Hindi and Marathi.
--><!--
The character after madhya is just a couple of dots in the facsimile. It could be a remnant of me, or it could be a visarga plus some scratches. Halder's editor notes, "why not madhye?" but this is probably based on the wrong assumption that the reading is madhya and madhyame is Halder's emendation, not a restoration of damaged text.
--><lb n="35"/>daṇḍapālī-grāmasya<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> paścimena yāvad aparā gartteti||<!--
The closing punctuation mark is a regular double daṇḍa, rather low in height.
--></p>
